  "prompt": "What causes cotton fabric to shrink? Heated water, cool water or both?",
  "response": "Cotton fabric can shrink due to exposure to heat, particularly hot water and high drying temperatures. Here's a breakdown:\n\n1. **Hot Water**: Washing cotton in hot water (above 130\u00b0F or 54\u00b0C) can cause the fibers to contract and shrink. This is because the heat relaxes the tension in the fibers, allowing them to tighten and shorten.\n\n2. **Cool Water**: Washing cotton in cool or cold water is less likely to cause shrinkage, as the fibers are not exposed to the same level of heat-induced tension release.\n\n3. **Dryer Heat**: Even if you wash cotton in cool water, drying it on high heat can still cause shrinkage. The combination of heat and tumbling can further tighten the fibers.\n\nTo minimize shrinkage, it's best to wash cotton in cool or warm water and air-dry it or use a low-heat setting in the dryer. Pre-washed or pre-shrunk cotton fabrics are also less prone to shrinking.",
